{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":1000,"text":"I was trying to think, how is sync connected to happiness,"},{"time":3000,"text":"and it occurred to me that for some reason we take pleasure in synchronizing."},{"time":10000,"text":"We like to dance together, we like singing together."},{"time":13000,"text":"And so, if you'll put up with this, I would like to enlist your help"},{"time":18000,"text":"with a first experiment today. The experiment is --"},{"time":22000,"text":"and I notice, by the way, that when you applauded,"},{"time":25000,"text":"that you did it in a typical North American way,"},{"time":27000,"text":"that is, you were raucous and incoherent."},{"time":31000,"text":"You were not organized. It didn't even occur to you to clap in unison."},{"time":36000,"text":"Do you think you could do it? I would like to see if this audience would --"},{"time":40000,"text":"no, you haven't practiced, as far as I know --"},{"time":42000,"text":"can you get it together to clap in sync?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":46000,"text":"(Clapping)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":56000,"text":"Whoa! Now, that's what we call emergent behavior."}]},{"cues":[{"time":58000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":60000,"text":"So I didn't expect that, but -- I mean, I expected you could synchronize."},{"time":64000,"text":"It didn't occur to me you'd increase your frequency."},{"time":67000,"text":"It's interesting."}]},{"cues":[{"time":69000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":72000,"text":"So what do we make of that? First of all, we know that you're all brilliant."},{"time":76000,"text":"This is a room full of intelligent people, highly sensitive."},{"time":80000,"text":"Some trained musicians out there."},{"time":83000,"text":"Is that what enabled you to synchronize?"},{"time":85000,"text":"So to put the question a little more seriously,"},{"time":88000,"text":"let's ask ourselves what are the minimum requirements for what you just did,"},{"time":92000,"text":"for spontaneous synchronization."},{"time":95000,"text":"Do you need, for instance, to be as smart as you are?"},{"time":99000,"text":"Do you even need a brain at all just to synchronize?"},{"time":106000,"text":"Do you need to be alive? I mean, that's a spooky thought, right?"},{"time":111000,"text":"Inanimate objects that might spontaneously synchronize themselves."},{"time":116000,"text":"It's real. In fact, I'll try to explain today that sync is maybe one of,"},{"time":123000,"text":"if not one of the most, perhaps the most pervasive drive in all of nature."},{"time":127000,"text":"It extends from the subatomic scale to the farthest reaches of the cosmos."},{"time":133000,"text":"It's a deep tendency toward order in nature"},{"time":137000,"text":"that opposes what we've all been taught about entropy."},{"time":140000,"text":"I mean, I'm not saying the law of entropy is wrong -- it's not."},{"time":143000,"text":"But there is a countervailing force in the universe --"},{"time":145000,"text":"the tendency towards spontaneous order. And so that's our theme."}]},{"cues":[{"time":150000,"text":"Now, to get into that, let me begin with what might have occurred to you immediately"},{"time":154000,"text":"when you hear that we're talking about synchrony in nature,"},{"time":158000,"text":"which is the glorious example of birds that flock together,"},{"time":164000,"text":"or fish swimming in organized schools."},{"time":168000,"text":"So these are not particularly intelligent creatures,"},{"time":172000,"text":"and yet, as we'll see, they exhibit beautiful ballets."},{"time":177000,"text":"This is from a BBC show called \"Predators,\""},{"time":179000,"text":"and what we're looking at here are examples of synchrony that have to do with defense."},{"time":185000,"text":"When you're small and vulnerable, like these starlings,"},{"time":188000,"text":"or like the fish, it helps to swarm to avoid predators, to confuse predators."},{"time":197000,"text":"Let me be quiet for a second because this is so gorgeous."},{"time":215000,"text":"For a long time, biologists were puzzled by this behavior,"},{"time":218000,"text":"wondering how it could be possible."},{"time":221000,"text":"We're so used to choreography giving rise to synchrony."},{"time":225000,"text":"These creatures are not choreographed."},{"time":227000,"text":"They're choreographing themselves."}]},{"cues":[{"time":231000,"text":"And only today is science starting to figure out how it works."},{"time":235000,"text":"I'll show you a computer model made by Iain Couzin, a researcher at Oxford,"},{"time":241000,"text":"that shows how swarms work."},{"time":243000,"text":"There are just three simple rules."},{"time":246000,"text":"First, all the individuals are only aware of their nearest neighbors."},{"time":251000,"text":"Second, all the individuals have a tendency to line up."},{"time":255000,"text":"And third, they're all attracted to each other,"},{"time":258000,"text":"but they try to keep a small distance apart."},{"time":261000,"text":"And when you build those three rules in,"},{"time":264000,"text":"automatically you start to see swarms"},{"time":266000,"text":"that look very much like fish schools or bird flocks."},{"time":270000,"text":"Now, fish like to stay close together, about a body length apart."},{"time":274000,"text":"Birds try to stay about three or four body lengths apart."},{"time":277000,"text":"But except for that difference, the rules are the same for both."}]},{"cues":[{"time":286000,"text":"Now, all this changes when a predator enters the scene."},{"time":291000,"text":"There's a fourth rule: when a predator's coming, get out of the way."},{"time":305000,"text":"Here on the model you see the predator attacking."},{"time":310000,"text":"The prey move out in random directions,"},{"time":312000,"text":"and then the rule of attraction brings them back together again,"},{"time":315000,"text":"so there's this constant splitting and reforming."},{"time":319000,"text":"And you see that in nature."},{"time":329000,"text":"Keep in mind that, although it looks as if each individual is acting to cooperate,"},{"time":335000,"text":"what's really going on is a kind of selfish Darwinian behavior."},{"time":339000,"text":"Each is scattering away at random to try to save its scales or feathers."},{"time":345000,"text":"That is, out of the desire to save itself,"},{"time":348000,"text":"each creature is following these rules,"},{"time":351000,"text":"and that leads to something that's safe for all of them."},{"time":353000,"text":"Even though it looks like they're thinking as a group, they're not."},{"time":374000,"text":"You might wonder what exactly is the advantage to being in a swarm,"},{"time":377000,"text":"so you can think of several."}]},{"cues":[{"time":379000,"text":"As I say, if you're in a swarm, your odds of being the unlucky one"},{"time":383000,"text":"are reduced as compared to a small group."},{"time":387000,"text":"There are many eyes to spot danger."},{"time":390000,"text":"And you'll see in the example with the starlings, with the birds,"},{"time":397000,"text":"when this peregrine hawk is about to attack them,"},{"time":399000,"text":"that actually waves of panic can propagate,"},{"time":402000,"text":"sending messages over great distances."},{"time":405000,"text":"You'll see -- let's see, it's coming up possibly at the very end -- maybe not."},{"time":414000,"text":"Information can be sent over half a kilometer away"},{"time":417000,"text":"in a very short time through this mechanism."},{"time":422000,"text":"Yes, it's happening here."},{"time":424000,"text":"See if you can see those waves propagating through the swarm."},{"time":428000,"text":"It's beautiful. The birds are, we sort of understand, we think,"},{"time":432000,"text":"from that computer model, what's going on."},{"time":434000,"text":"As I say, it's just those three simple rules,"},{"time":436000,"text":"plus the one about watch out for predators."}]},{"cues":[{"time":438000,"text":"There doesn't seem to be anything mystical about this."},{"time":441000,"text":"We don't, however, really understand at a mathematical level."},{"time":444000,"text":"I'm a mathematician. We would like to be able to understand better."},{"time":448000,"text":"I mean, I showed you a computer model, but a computer is not understanding."},{"time":451000,"text":"A computer is, in a way, just another experiment."},{"time":454000,"text":"We would really like to have a deeper insight into how this works"},{"time":457000,"text":"and to understand, you know, exactly where this organization comes from."},{"time":462000,"text":"How do the rules give rise to the patterns?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":464000,"text":"There is one case that we have begun to understand better,"},{"time":467000,"text":"and it's the case of fireflies."},{"time":470000,"text":"If you see fireflies in North America,"},{"time":472000,"text":"like so many North American sorts of things,"},{"time":474000,"text":"they tend to be independent operators. They ignore each other."},{"time":478000,"text":"They each do their own thing, flashing on and off,"},{"time":480000,"text":"paying no attention to their neighbors."},{"time":482000,"text":"But in Southeast Asia -- places like Thailand or Malaysia or Borneo --"},{"time":487000,"text":"there's a beautiful cooperative behavior that occurs among male fireflies."},{"time":492000,"text":"You can see it every night along the river banks."},{"time":495000,"text":"The trees, mangrove trees, are filled with fireflies communicating with light."},{"time":500000,"text":"Specifically, it's male fireflies who are all flashing in perfect time together,"},{"time":505000,"text":"in perfect synchrony, to reinforce a message to the females."},{"time":509000,"text":"And the message, as you can imagine, is \"Come hither. Mate with me.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":514000,"text":"(Music)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":521000,"text":"In a second I'm going to show you a slow motion of a single firefly"},{"time":525000,"text":"so that you can get a sense. This is a single frame."},{"time":528000,"text":"Then on, and then off -- a 30th of a second, there."},{"time":533000,"text":"And then watch this whole river bank, and watch how precise the synchrony is."},{"time":540000,"text":"On, more on and then off."},{"time":549000,"text":"The combined light from these beetles -- these are actually tiny beetles --"},{"time":552000,"text":"is so bright that fishermen out at sea can use them"},{"time":555000,"text":"as navigating beacons to find their way back to their home rivers. It's stunning."},{"time":559000,"text":"For a long time it was not believed"},{"time":561000,"text":"when the first Western travelers, like Sir Francis Drake,"},{"time":564000,"text":"went to Thailand and came back with tales of this unbelievable spectacle."},{"time":568000,"text":"No one believed them."},{"time":570000,"text":"We don't see anything like this in Europe or in the West."},{"time":573000,"text":"And for a long time, even after it was documented,"},{"time":576000,"text":"it was thought to be some kind of optical illusion."},{"time":578000,"text":"Scientific papers were published saying it was twitching eyelids"},{"time":581000,"text":"that explained it, or, you know, a human being's tendency"},{"time":585000,"text":"to see patterns where there are none."},{"time":587000,"text":"But I hope you've convinced yourself now, with this nighttime video,"},{"time":590000,"text":"that they really were very well synchronized."}]},{"cues":[{"time":593000,"text":"Okay, well, the issue then is, do we need to be alive"},{"time":596000,"text":"to see this kind of spontaneous order,"},{"time":598000,"text":"and I've already hinted that the answer is no."},{"time":603000,"text":"Well, you don't have to be a whole creature."},{"time":605000,"text":"You can even be just a single cell."},{"time":607000,"text":"Like, take, for instance, your pacemaker cells in your heart right now."},{"time":610000,"text":"They're keeping you alive."},{"time":612000,"text":"Every beat of your heart depends on this crucial region, the sinoatrial node,"},{"time":617000,"text":"which has about 10,000 independent cells that would each beep,"},{"time":621000,"text":"have an electrical rhythm -- a voltage up and down --"},{"time":624000,"text":"to send a signal to the ventricles to pump."},{"time":627000,"text":"Now, your pacemaker is not a single cell."},{"time":630000,"text":"It's this democracy of 10,000 cells that all have to fire in unison"},{"time":633000,"text":"for the pacemaker to work correctly."}]},{"cues":[{"time":636000,"text":"I don't want to give you the idea that synchrony is always a good idea."},{"time":639000,"text":"If you have epilepsy, there is an instance of billions of brain cells, or at least millions,"},{"time":644000,"text":"discharging in pathological concert."},{"time":648000,"text":"So this tendency towards order is not always a good thing."},{"time":652000,"text":"You don't have to be alive. You don't have to be even a single cell."},{"time":655000,"text":"If you look, for instance, at how lasers work,"},{"time":658000,"text":"that would be a case of atomic synchrony."},{"time":661000,"text":"In a laser, what makes laser light so different from the light above my head here"},{"time":665000,"text":"is that this light is incoherent --"},{"time":667000,"text":"many different colors and different frequencies,"},{"time":670000,"text":"sort of like the way you clapped initially --"},{"time":673000,"text":"but if you were a laser, it would be rhythmic applause."},{"time":676000,"text":"It would be all atoms pulsating in unison,"},{"time":678000,"text":"emitting light of one color, one frequency."}]},{"cues":[{"time":682000,"text":"Now comes the very risky part of my talk,"},{"time":685000,"text":"which is to demonstrate that inanimate things can synchronize."},{"time":689000,"text":"Hold your breath for me."},{"time":691000,"text":"What I have here are two empty water bottles."},{"time":698000,"text":"This is not Keith Barry doing a magic trick."},{"time":700000,"text":"This is a klutz just playing with some water bottles."},{"time":705000,"text":"I have some metronomes here."},{"time":710000,"text":"Can you hear that?"},{"time":714000,"text":"All right, so, I've got a metronome,"},{"time":716000,"text":"and it's the world's smallest metronome, the -- well, I shouldn't advertise."},{"time":720000,"text":"Anyway, so this is the world's smallest metronome."},{"time":723000,"text":"I've set it on the fastest setting, and I'm going to now take"},{"time":726000,"text":"another one set to the same setting."},{"time":730000,"text":"We can try this first. If I just put them on the table together,"},{"time":735000,"text":"there's no reason for them to synchronize, and they probably won't."}]},{"cues":[{"time":744000,"text":"Maybe you'd better listen to them. I'll stand here."},{"time":751000,"text":"What I'm hoping is that they might just drift apart"},{"time":753000,"text":"because their frequencies aren't perfectly the same."},{"time":763000,"text":"Right? They did."},{"time":765000,"text":"They were in sync for a while, but then they drifted apart."},{"time":769000,"text":"And the reason is that they're not able to communicate."},{"time":771000,"text":"Now, you might think that's a bizarre idea."},{"time":773000,"text":"How can metronomes communicate?"},{"time":776000,"text":"Well, they can communicate through mechanical forces."},{"time":779000,"text":"So I'm going to give them a chance to do that."},{"time":781000,"text":"I also want to wind this one up a bit. How can they communicate?"},{"time":784000,"text":"I'm going to put them on a movable platform,"},{"time":786000,"text":"which is the \"Guide to Graduate Study at Cornell.\" Okay? So here it is."},{"time":795000,"text":"Let's see if we can get this to work."},{"time":799000,"text":"My wife pointed out to me that it will work better if I put both on at the same time"},{"time":803000,"text":"because otherwise the whole thing will tip over."},{"time":805000,"text":"All right. So there we go. Let's see. OK, I'm not trying to cheat --"},{"time":812000,"text":"let me start them out of sync. No, hard to even do that."}]},{"cues":[{"time":830000,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":834000,"text":"All right. So before any one goes out of sync, I'll just put those right there."}]},{"cues":[{"time":839000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":840000,"text":"Now, that might seem a bit whimsical,"},{"time":842000,"text":"but this pervasiveness of this tendency towards spontaneous order"},{"time":847000,"text":"sometimes has unexpected consequences."},{"time":851000,"text":"And a clear case of that,"},{"time":853000,"text":"was something that happened in London in the year 2000."},{"time":856000,"text":"The Millennium Bridge was supposed to be the pride of London --"},{"time":859000,"text":"a beautiful new footbridge erected across the Thames,"},{"time":863000,"text":"first river crossing in over 100 years in London."},{"time":867000,"text":"There was a big competition for the design of this bridge,"},{"time":870000,"text":"and the winning proposal was submitted by an unusual team --"},{"time":874000,"text":"in the TED spirit, actually -- of an architect --"},{"time":877000,"text":"perhaps the greatest architect in the United Kingdom, Lord Norman Foster --"},{"time":881000,"text":"working with an artist, a sculptor, Sir Anthony Caro,"},{"time":886000,"text":"and an engineering firm, Ove Arup."},{"time":890000,"text":"And together they submitted a design based on Lord Foster's vision,"},{"time":895000,"text":"which was -- he remembered as a kid reading Flash Gordon comic books,"},{"time":899000,"text":"and he said that when Flash Gordon would come to an abyss,"},{"time":902000,"text":"he would shoot what today would be a kind of a light saber."}]},{"cues":[{"time":905000,"text":"He would shoot his light saber across the abyss, making a blade of light,"},{"time":909000,"text":"and then scamper across on this blade of light."},{"time":911000,"text":"He said, \"That's the vision I want to give to London."},{"time":913000,"text":"I want a blade of light across the Thames.\""},{"time":917000,"text":"So they built the blade of light,"},{"time":919000,"text":"and it's a very thin ribbon of steel, the world's --"},{"time":925000,"text":"probably the flattest and thinnest suspension bridge there is,"},{"time":928000,"text":"with cables that are out on the side."},{"time":931000,"text":"You're used to suspension bridges with big droopy cables on the top."},{"time":934000,"text":"These cables were on the side of the bridge,"},{"time":937000,"text":"like if you took a rubber band and stretched it taut across the Thames --"},{"time":941000,"text":"that's what's holding up this bridge."},{"time":943000,"text":"Now, everyone was very excited to try it out."},{"time":945000,"text":"On opening day, thousands of Londoners came out, and something happened."},{"time":950000,"text":"And within two days the bridge was closed to the public."},{"time":954000,"text":"So I want to first show you some interviews with people"},{"time":959000,"text":"who were on the bridge on opening day, who will describe what happened."}]},{"cues":[{"time":962000,"text":"Man: It really started moving sideways and slightly up and down,"},{"time":967000,"text":"rather like being on the boat."}]},{"cues":[{"time":970000,"text":"Woman: Yeah, it felt unstable, and it was very windy,"},{"time":973000,"text":"and I remember it had lots of flags up and down the sides, so you could definitely --"},{"time":977000,"text":"there was something going on sideways, it felt, maybe."}]},{"cues":[{"time":980000,"text":"Interviewer: Not up and down? Boy: No."}]},{"cues":[{"time":982000,"text":"Interviewer: And not forwards and backwards? Boy: No."}]},{"cues":[{"time":984000,"text":"Interviewer: Just sideways. About how much was it moving, do you think?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":987000,"text":"Boy: It was about --"}]},{"cues":[{"time":989000,"text":"Interviewer: I mean, that much, or this much?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":991000,"text":"Boy: About the second one."}]},{"cues":[{"time":993000,"text":"Interviewer: This much? Boy: Yeah."}]},{"cues":[{"time":995000,"text":"Man: It was at least six, six to eight inches, I would have thought."}]},{"cues":[{"time":998000,"text":"Interviewer: Right, so, at least this much? Man: Oh, yes."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1000000,"text":"Woman: I remember wanting to get off."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1002000,"text":"Interviewer: Oh, did you? Woman: Yeah. It felt odd."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1004000,"text":"Interviewer: So it was enough to be scary? Woman: Yeah, but I thought that was just me."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1010000,"text":"Interviewer: Ah! Now, tell me why you had to do this?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1013000,"text":"Boy: We had to do this because, to keep in balance"},{"time":1015000,"text":"because if you didn't keep your balance,"},{"time":1017000,"text":"then you would just fall over about, like, to the left or right, about 45 degrees."},{"time":1023000,"text":"Interviewer: So just show me how you walk normally. Right."},{"time":1028000,"text":"And then show me what it was like when the bridge started to go. Right."},{"time":1033000,"text":"So you had to deliberately push your feet out sideways and --"},{"time":1037000,"text":"oh, and short steps?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1039000,"text":"Man: That's right. And it seemed obvious to me"},{"time":1042000,"text":"that it was probably the number of people on it."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1046000,"text":"Interviewer: Were they deliberately walking in step, or anything like that?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1050000,"text":"Man: No, they just had to conform to the movement of the bridge."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1054000,"text":"Steven Strogatz: All right, so that already gives you a hint of what happened."},{"time":1057000,"text":"Think of the bridge as being like this platform."},{"time":1061000,"text":"Think of the people as being like metronomes."},{"time":1064000,"text":"Now, you might not be used to thinking of yourself as a metronome,"},{"time":1067000,"text":"but after all, we do walk like -- I mean, we oscillate back and forth as we walk."},{"time":1071000,"text":"And especially if we start to walk like those people did, right?"},{"time":1074000,"text":"They all showed this strange sort of skating gait"},{"time":1078000,"text":"that they adopted once the bridge started to move."},{"time":1081000,"text":"And so let me show you now the footage of the bridge."},{"time":1084000,"text":"But also, after you see the bridge on opening day, you'll see an interesting clip"},{"time":1088000,"text":"of work done by a bridge engineer at Cambridge named Allan McRobie,"},{"time":1093000,"text":"who figured out what happened on the bridge,"},{"time":1095000,"text":"and who built a bridge simulator to explain exactly what the problem was."},{"time":1099000,"text":"It was a kind of unintended positive feedback loop"},{"time":1103000,"text":"between the way the people walked and the way the bridge began to move,"},{"time":1106000,"text":"that engineers knew nothing about."},{"time":1108000,"text":"Actually, I think the first person you'll see"},{"time":1110000,"text":"is the young engineer who was put in charge of this project. Okay."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1115000,"text":"(Video) Interviewer: Did anyone get hurt? Engineer: No."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1117000,"text":"Interviewer: Right. So it was quite small -- Engineer: Yes. Interviewer: -- but real?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1120000,"text":"Engineer: Absolutely. Interviewer: You thought, \"Oh, bother.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":1123000,"text":"Engineer: I felt I was disappointed about it."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1126000,"text":"We'd spent a lot of time designing this bridge, and we'd analyzed it,"},{"time":1130000,"text":"we'd checked it to codes -- to heavier loads than the codes --"},{"time":1133000,"text":"and here it was doing something that we didn't know about."},{"time":1136000,"text":"Interviewer: You didn't expect. Engineer: Exactly."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1138000,"text":"Narrator: The most dramatic and shocking footage"},{"time":1141000,"text":"shows whole sections of the crowd -- hundreds of people --"},{"time":1144000,"text":"apparently rocking from side to side in unison,"},{"time":1146000,"text":"not only with each other, but with the bridge."},{"time":1149000,"text":"This synchronized movement seemed to be driving the bridge."},{"time":1153000,"text":"But how could the crowd become synchronized?"},{"time":1156000,"text":"Was there something special about the Millennium Bridge that caused this effect?"},{"time":1160000,"text":"This was to be the focus of the investigation."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1164000,"text":"Interviewer: Well, at last the simulated bridge is finished, and I can make it wobble."},{"time":1171000,"text":"Now, Allan, this is all your fault, isn't it? Allan McRobie: Yes."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1175000,"text":"Interviewer: You designed this, yes, this simulated bridge,"},{"time":1177000,"text":"and this, you reckon, mimics the action of the real bridge?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1180000,"text":"AM: It captures a lot of the physics, yes."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1182000,"text":"Interviewer: Right. So if we get on it, we should be able to wobble it, yes?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1188000,"text":"Allan McRobie is a bridge engineer from Cambridge who wrote to me,"},{"time":1191000,"text":"suggesting that a bridge simulator ought to wobble"},{"time":1194000,"text":"in the same way as the real bridge --"},{"time":1196000,"text":"provided we hung it on pendulums of exactly the right length."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1198000,"text":"AM: This one's only a couple of tons, so it's fairly easy to get going."},{"time":1201000,"text":"Just by walking. Interviewer: Well, it's certainly going now."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1204000,"text":"AM: It doesn't have to be a real dangle. Just walk. It starts to go."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1207000,"text":"Interviewer: It's actually quite difficult to walk.\n"},{"time":1210000,"text":"You have to be careful where you put your feet down, don't you,\n"},{"time":1213000,"text":"because if you get it wrong, it just throws you off your feet."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1216000,"text":"AM: It certainly affects the way you walk, yes. You can't walk normally on it."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1221000,"text":"Interviewer: No. If you try and put one foot in front of another,"},{"time":1223000,"text":"it's moving your feet away from under you. AM: Yes."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1226000,"text":"Interviewer: So you've got to put your feet out sideways."},{"time":1229000,"text":"So already, the simulator is making me walk in exactly the same way"},{"time":1232000,"text":"as our witnesses walked on the real bridge."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1234000,"text":"AM: ... ice-skating gait. There isn't all this sort of snake way of walking."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1237000,"text":"Interviewer: For a more convincing experiment,"},{"time":1239000,"text":"I wanted my own opening-day crowd, the sound check team."},{"time":1242000,"text":"Their instructions: just walk normally."},{"time":1254000,"text":"It's really intriguing because none of these people is trying to drive it."},{"time":1258000,"text":"They're all having some difficulty walking."},{"time":1261000,"text":"And the only way you can walk comfortably is by getting in step."},{"time":1264000,"text":"But then, of course, everyone is driving the bridge."},{"time":1269000,"text":"You can't help it. You're actually forced by the movement of the bridge to get into step,"},{"time":1274000,"text":"and therefore to drive it to move further."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1280000,"text":"SS: All right, well, with that from the Ministry of Silly Walks,"},{"time":1284000,"text":"maybe I'd better end. I see I've gone over."},{"time":1287000,"text":"But I hope that you'll go outside and see the world in a new way,"},{"time":1290000,"text":"to see all the amazing synchrony around us. Thank you."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1293000,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}